node.text: ... because what is a staircase if not a vertical room?! Aly and Tyler of @chasingpapercity are putting their own spin on CIRCA's one-room journey series with this walk-and-talk inside the work-in-progress that is the stair hall of their c. 1900 Victorian. Starting on the first floor and climbing up, up to the attic, listen to Aly and Tyler's plans are to restore some aspects, (such as the lovely oak flooring, adding true stained glass windows) and renovate others (like creating the double-height bookcase of your wildest dreams!). Before you even have to ask, YES, @chasingpapercity fully intends to include a fancy library ladder -- the technical term, as Aly reminds us, is "Beauty and the Beast-style" ladder. If anyone watching works in building code enforcement, shield your eyes because some of the conditions Tyler and Aly have inherited would certainly not pass muster today. But after a bit more work is complete, @chasingpapercity will not only make code-focused folks rest easy, this house will have a completely new attitude ... and a happy family to call it home! Thanks so much, Aly and Tyler, for sharing with CIRCA! #circaoldhouses

node.text: What do tulip tables 🌷, weiner mobiles 🌭, Victrolas 🎶, and houses 🏠 have in common? They can all be patented! Enjoy the replay of our live chat with Tom Rinaldi, author of “PATENTED” (out now from @phaidonsnaps). Follow @designpatentdaily to learn more than you ever imagined was possible about everyday objects and what their design evolution over time can reveal to us. We’re talking toasters and tape dispensers, automobiles and egg cartons … it’s incredible! Thanks so much @rinaldit2 for spending time with us 🙌🏽 #circaoldhouses

node.text: This is a story about a dog and his farmhouse. Charlie's been directing his family of hoomans -- including Justyna, the voice behind @ahouseforcharlie -- in the restoration of his 1905 farmhouse for some time now. Lucky us, he's kindly given the green light for a tour of the transformed dining room! Enjoy the Greene County summer sunlight, in the Catskills region of New York, as Justyna recounts how the space went from tragic (referring to the multitude of deceased rodents found in the walls when work first began, in 2019) to point of pride. Lovers of #secondhandfirst and Facebook Marketplace will rejoice in some of the second-hand finds @ahouseforcharlie has gathered together to make the dining room feel layered and welcoming. Here's to warm summer days enjoying a fresh farm breakfast at the dining room table, with the sunlight streaming through all the way to the kitchen (A+ move removing that wall, Justyna!). Thank you, @ahouseforcharlie, for sharing your piece of #Catskills magic with us. #circaoldhouses

node.text: Welcome to the sublime Adirondacks, where soft, green moss carpets the forest floor and sweet birdsong fills the air! Our latest #CIRCAroadtrip brought us to @thelorca #ADK, an 8-room motel which @julianandjulian and his partners (you remember @cocoandbreezy from our chat about their first project, in the #Catskills; and let's not forget @dleiberman!) are refurbishing. On a walk in the woods with Julian, we learned a bit about what's driving the team's decisions to create a Lorca experience in the Adirondacks. Hints: function, simplicity, beauty. @crisapena spent three cozy nights and three picturesque days exploring the Adirondack High Peaks with The Lorca #ADK, in Indian Lake, as her base camp. Jump to our saved Stories Highlight to revisit misty mornings kayaking on the lake, refreshing dips in crystal-clear swimming holes, and so much more. Be sure to follow @thelorca and make plans to experience the #ADK or the #Catskills properties this summer. Thank you, @julianandjulian, for your incredible hospitality! #circaoldhouses

node.text: THIS, dear friends, is how you do a gallery wall! And THIS, dear friends of old house preservation, is how you renovate while preserving original details and historic character! Indeed, Susan and William Brinson from @houseofbrinson get all the CIRCA gold stars for their work in the main bathroom at Stonyford, their Hudson Valley, New York, home. On our final #PreservationMonth one-room journey in partnership with @fireclaytile, we're stepping inside this 1802 home to see how @houseofbrinson seamlessly integrated updates within the context of their historically rich home. Marvel at how beautifully the tile by @fireclaytile, in color Cyclone, complements the creamy, crackley *original* subway tiles. And that corner detail Susan points out to us? #TodayILearned that's called a fingercove -- and yes, Fireclay make those! The antique rugs, the carefully curated gallery wall, the toilet typography (yes, you read that right!) is all so heavenly. Got questions (of course you do) about how or where or why @houseofbrinson achieved this final design? Head over to her page and tap the link in bio for answers galore! Thank you so much, Susan and William @houseofbrinson, for this friendly invitation inside Stonyford. #circaoldhouses

node.text: We're celebrating Emily Starr Alfano's kitchen just in the nick of time -- she's about to move! Before @mstarrevdesign trades her c. 1830s #FarmhouseDiAlfano for another lovely old house, we're stepping through the side door, pausing a moment in the mudroom (which is also the laundry room ... which is also the coffee nook!), and taking a spin around Emily's kitchen. It's all set against a backdrop of beautifully expressive @fireclaytile Handmade Brick in Klamath. Emily indulges us all the textural close-ups we old house lovers crave. Each brick's individual indentations and tone make for a room with dimension and character. HOT TIP: @fireclaytile recently debuted Norman Brick, inspired by the extra-wide bricks popularized in America during the 20th century and found on some of the most iconic architecture of the era (think Frank Lloyd Wright's Robie House in Chicago, to name just one!). From brick to breadboards to Bruno in a basket, Emily's kitchen is the kind of space you want to spend all your time -- especially those sun-drenched afternoons like she's enjoying here! Thank you so much @mstarrevdesign for this thoughtful talk, and to @fireclaytile for connecting CIRCA with a fellow old house steward! #circaoldhouses

node.text: One word: EICHLER! Our three-part IGTV one-room journey collaboration with @fireclaytile kicks off with a kitchen tour from @destinationeichler. May is #PreservationMonth, and we're celebrating homeowners who've breathed new life into their old house in tandem with @fireclaytile, the California-based company with a commitment to craft, history and sustainability (did you know: Fireclay is a proud supporter of the National Parks Conservation Association @npcapics?). First up is Karen Nepacena of @destinationeichler, whose 1959 home was built by real estate developer Joseph Eichler. From @docomomo_us: "After World War II, developer Joseph Eichler offered middle-class Californians a slice of the 'American Dream' with high-style, modernist, suburban homes at affordable prices. What Eichler offered was rare – tract homes designed by notable, talented architects ..." In @destinationeichler's case, it was the firm of Jones & Emmons. Karen and her husband, John @eichler_diy, have documented their home's revival and a big part of that was working with the expressive, colorful products from @fireclaytile to enliven their kitchen with bold #MidCenturyModern geometric character (here, Tiki Blue Diamond Escher, which Karen and John installed themselves). I'm jealous just thinking of pouring a morning cup of coffee with the California sunshine streaming through the floor-to-ceiling windows and brightening the entire space. Thank you @destinationeichler @eichler_diy for sharing a look inside your Eichler with CIRCA! #circaoldhouses #ModernMonday #MidCentury

node.title: Karen (@destinationeichler), San Francisco Bay Area, CA

node.text: Thank you to everyone (wow, so many of you!) for spending your Saturday morning touring this historic edifice with CIRCA for #JanesWalkNYC with @mas_nyc. We’re so grateful to @raginskaya for this incredible insider’s look! Below, the inscription from the exterior of the Williamsburg Savings Bank Tower: "To our depositors past and present this building is dedicated. By their industry and thrift they have built homes and educated children, opened the door of opportunity to youth and made age comfortable, independent and dignified. By those sturdy virtues they have obtained their ambitions, swept aside the petty distinctions of class and birth and so maintained the true spirit of American democracy.” #circaoldhouses

node.text: Consider this post a love letter to original wood floors, to the craftspeople who designed and installed them generations ago, and certainly to the old house lovers like Miranda @easthill_revival who bring them back to life! This one-room journey of #CrestviewHouse, her current project in Belleville, Ontario, is HYPNOTIZING ... no words can do these floors justice (though please, do use yours to lavish praise upon them in the comments!). And if #IHaveThisThingWithFloors somehow isn't your thing, just #LookUp and feast your eyes upon the ceiling medallions and crown molding in both rooms. I'm on pins and needles to see these rooms finished -- and I predict that this kitchen just may be the closest thing to culinary heaven we'll ever see! Thank you so much @easthill_revival for sharing this glimpse into #CrestviewHouse with CIRCA! #circaoldhouses

node.text: For the first time ever, our one-room journey has a dress code: cozy Sunday pj's and fluffy slippers, required! Zip up your onesie pajamas and join Dakarai and Kamaria of @detroithoodstead for a quick spin around their perfectly peachy vintage bathroom. Or is it? As Kamaria explains, her initial take on the tile was peach and salmon. I might even call it blush ... but I'd be wrong! As @detroithoodstead dove into research for 1950s bathroom trends, theirs seemed reminiscent of the era-defining "Mamie pink," named after First Lady Mamie Eisenhower. So, presidential pink it is! Paired with a vintage sink and an original double-hung window that absolutely floods this petite room with light, and you've got an old house bathroom that just radiates with warmth and happiness (hence my obsession with it since @detroithoodstead first shared a glimpse in March). Thank you so much, Kamaria and Dakarai, for inviting CIRCA to your Sunday virtual old house pajama party! #circaoldhouses

node.text: Private investment, public benefit — that was a key takeaway from our walk + talk this morning with Kate Wood @worthpreserving on the subject of historic tax credits. In the small hamlet of Germantown, NY, Kate and her family have invested in this early 1800s house and realized an incredible transformation incentivized by the historic tax credit program. Watch and learn the basics, from determining eligibility to developing your work plan to collaborating with the State Historic Preservation Office (that’s the “SHPO” we reference), all to create a project that is respectful of history while also comfortable for contemporary living. Thank you, Kate (and camera crew @travisbrockkennedy!) for spending your Saturday with CIRCA! #circaoldhouses #rehabilitation #preservation

node.text: The ultimate kitchen #GlowUp of 2021 … and it’s only March! Before: low ceiling, can lights and just an absence of historic character (head to @thisyunkyhouse to see what this room looked like at the time of purchase, oof!). After: Zach and Hugh have transformed their Manayunk, PA, kitchen into the kind of room where we all want to spend our weekends, baking banana bread (Hugh, send me your recipe) and tending to our grande dame pothos! When @thisyunkyhouse first shared that a renovation was afoot, I wondered “what could they possibly have in store?” The answer: expose the beautiful beams to celebrate the structure and craftsmanship of their late-1800s rowhouse. As Zach shows us, there were a few finds that will make any old house-loving soul’s heart beat a little faster, like Roman numerals etched into the beams and square-head nails. @thisyunkyhouse, your kitchen project is a lesson in #LookUp if ever there was one. Thank you so much for sharing this (and your banana bread recipe — how many times do I have to ask?!) with CIRCA! #circaoldhouses

This farm-to-table inn comes with a few tenants 🐓🥦🐓🌽🐓🥒🐓🍅 🐓⁠⁠
⁠⁠
(Bryson City, NC)⁠⁠
-⁠⁠
From the listing with rob@bandbconsulting.us: Amazing investment opportunity in the hospitality hub of the Great Smokeys. A farm-to-table 10 guest room bed and breakfast for sale with 2 bedroom Inn Owner’s quarters with a private entrance.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Farm to Table Gourmet is an understatement. The Folkestone Inn has long been know for its delicious breakfasts. Now the mornings are even more scrumptious. The Folkestone Inn began in the early ’20s as a rural farmhouse surrounded by cornfields, gardens and pastures. Today, much of that farmstead feelings remains. The garden provides fresh herbs and veggies for the legendary farm-to-table breakfast. The beloved flock of hens provide the kitchen with the freshest eggs. The cornfield is now a sprawling front lawn with plenty of room to chase frisbees or do your morning yoga. Closer to the house, local craftsman homemade chairs surround a fire pit that comes life many evenings.⁠⁠
From downtown Bryson City going to the Folkestone Bed & Breakfast Inn you will pass the passenger, on and off ramp, for the Great Smokys Railroad. The Great Smokys Railroad has 53 miles of track with two tunnels and 25 bridges. This is a major tourist destination in Western North Carolinan for adults and children of all ages and and ideal for families. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The property is ideal for the environmental conscious buyer. Much of the food waste from the Inn is used to feed the “Free Ranging” chickens. Yes the chickens are free ranging during the day. Each evening they end up back at their chicken house on their own. All the meat proteins-bacon, sausage, ham-are cured and smoked at the Inn.⁠⁠
-⁠⁠

From the listing with @kellyandkellypropertiesinc: Welcome to the Girardeau House, ca. 1890. This Folk Victorian gem has been carefully renovated to allow for all the conveniences of modern living, while respectfully preserving the historical integrity of the home. A National Register of Historic Places home, the footprint remains intact since its construction and boasts magnificent architectural details including the original hardwood floors, crown moldings and pocket doors. A large center hallway with a grand staircase greets guests. Ten-foot ceilings in the main living areas create an open feel through the house, kept cozy by eight fireplaces, offset by period mantles and adorned with over-mantles and mirrors. The stunning renovation/restoration of this bespoke abode includes an upgraded kitchen, walk-in pantry, and 8×11 first floor flex room for studio/exercise/hobby room. A primary bedroom with en suite and clawfoot tub on the main affords contemporary convenience with easy access to the kitchen, living and dining areas. The upstairs features a spacious sitting room, three additional bedrooms and two full baths. Fronting a majestic canopy road lined with Live Oaks and ancient Sago Palms, this remarkable Victorian features first and second floor wraparound porches on the facade with original gingerbread details on several sides of the exterior; perfect for relaxation or entertaining. The back porch overlooks mature landscaping including a rose garden, Victorian style crested 8×12 greenhouse, and a 16×20 playhouse or potting shed, creating garden-like views and comfortable outdoor living. An oversized 24×24 garage/workshop compliments the main dwelling with coordinating shakes and shingles. Updated electrical & plumbing throughout, along with an irrigation system, and separate upstairs/downstairs HVAC systems. The only single-family home in Monticello recognized as a Florida Heritage Site [F-1132] by the Florida Department of State. Bed & breakfast use is possible with current R-1 city zoning.⁠⁠

node.text:
An ode to historic hearths and original floors!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
($1,695,000 / Burnt Hills, NY)⁠⁠
-⁠⁠
From the listing with @sarah.hislop.realtor @selectsir @sothebysrealty: Charm abounds in this center-chimney colonial on ten acres Saratoga County, NY. Originally constructed circa 1800 in Clifton Park, in approximately 1986 the house was carefully disassembled, parts and pieces numbered, and moved to its current location so it could be rebuilt nestled into an apple orchard in Burnt Hills, but with a modern foundation, insulation and mechanicals.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Peaceful and serene describe the grounds of this property. Meandering through the driveway past the idyllic three stall red horse barn and fenced paddock as you approach the pasture, apple trees, pear trees and blueberry bushes, one can’t help but look forward to what’s next.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Wide board floors grace the home’s entirety, exposed beams, moldings, mantle pieces, wood wall treatments, five Rumford fireplaces, original doors and hand forged hardware; the house has been thoughtfully updated with modern amenities, such as zoned central air conditioning, solar panels, a whole house generator, a first floor laundry room with soapstone sink, large home office with gas fireplace, its own half bath and entrance from the exterior, high speed cable internet, a wine cellar and tasting room with wood planked walls, a home gym – heated and cooled, a heated garage with water, raised bed gardens with water, supplemental well, on demand hot water system, water filtration and softener systems and a full walk up attic with cedar closet.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
With three+ bedrooms, two full baths and two half baths, there’s quite a bit of versatility with the layout. The home office could easily be used as a first floor bedroom as it is adjacent to a full bath. Two more rooms that could be formal living and dining rooms, or perhaps a library or TV room, offer their own wood burning fireplaces. On the second floor there’s a spa bath with radiant heat flooring, three generously sized bedrooms and another flex space that could be used as a nursery, yoga room, craft room or playroom.⁠⁠
